const book8 = {
  title: "Exploring NestJS",
  handle: "exploringnestjs",
  state: "Published",

  chapters: [
    {
      title:
        "A Powerful Framework for Building Scalable Server-Side Applications",
      content: `<p>In the ever-evolving landscape of web development, choosing the right framework is crucial for building scalable and maintainable server-side applications. NestJS, a progressive Node.js framework, has emerged as a popular choice among developers for its robust features, modular architecture, and seamless integration with TypeScript. This article delves into the core aspects of NestJS, its benefits, and why it stands out in the crowded field of backend frameworks.</p><p></p><h3>What is NestJS?  </h3><p>NestJS is an open-source framework for building efficient, scalable, and enterprise-grade server-side applications. It leverages TypeScript by default (but also supports JavaScript) and draws inspiration from Angular's architecture, promoting the use of decorators, dependency injection, and modular structure. NestJS aims to provide an out-of-the-box application architecture that allows developers to create highly testable, scalable, and loosely coupled applications.</p><pre><code>import { Controller, Get } from '@nestjs/common';
import { UsersService } from './users.service';

@Controller('users')
export class UsersController {
  constructor(private readonly usersService: UsersService) {}

  @Get()
  findAll() {
    return this.usersService.findAll();
  }
}
</code></pre><ol><li><p><strong>TypeScript Integration:</strong></p><ul><li><p>NestJS is built with TypeScript, offering strong typing and advanced language features that enhance developer productivity and code maintainability. TypeScript helps catch errors at compile time, leading to more robust applications.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Modular Architecture:</strong></p><ul><li><p>NestJS encourages the use of modules to organize code into cohesive blocks, making it easier to manage and scale large applications. Each module encapsulates related components, such as controllers, services, and providers, promoting a clean and maintainable codebase.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Dependency Injection:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Inspired by Angular, NestJS utilizes a powerful dependency injection system, allowing developers to manage dependencies efficiently. This design pattern helps achieve loose coupling and enhances the testability of the application.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Decorators:</strong></p><ul><li><p>NestJS uses decorators to define metadata for classes and methods. These decorators simplify tasks such as routing, middleware configuration, and dependency injection, resulting in more readable and concise code.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Built-in Support for Microservices:</strong></p><ul><li><p>NestJS provides out-of-the-box support for building microservices and serverless applications. It includes transport strategies for messaging systems like RabbitMQ, Kafka, and MQTT, facilitating the creation of scalable distributed systems.</p></li></ul></li></ol><h3>Conclusion</h3><p>NestJS provides a powerful and flexible framework for building scalable server-side applications. Its use of TypeScript, modular architecture, and integration with modern technologies make it a compelling choice for developers. Whether you're building a monolithic application or a microservice architecture, NestJS offers the tools and features needed to create robust and maintainable codebases. By following the steps outlined in this article, you can get started with NestJS and begin leveraging its capabilities for your next project.</p>`,
    },
  ],
};

const book9 = {
  title: "Mastering React Hook Form",
  handle: "masteringreacthookform",
  state: "Published",

  chapters: [
    {
      title: "React Hook Form: A Comprehensive Guide",
      content: `<p>Managing forms in React applications can be challenging, especially when dealing with complex validations, dynamic fields, and performance concerns. React Hook Form is a popular library that simplifies form handling in React by leveraging hooks, making form state management intuitive and efficient. This article provides an in-depth look at React Hook Form, its benefits, and practical examples to help you integrate it seamlessly into your React projects.</p><p></p><h3>What is React Hook Form?</h3><p>React Hook Form is a lightweight library for managing forms in React applications. It focuses on reducing the amount of code needed for form handling while improving performance. By using React hooks, it allows developers to manage form state, validation, and submission with minimal boilerplate code.</p><p></p><h3>Key Features of React Hook Form</h3><ol><li><p><strong>Performance Optimization:</strong></p><ul><li><p>React Hook Form minimizes re-renders and leverages uncontrolled components, resulting in better performance compared to other form libraries.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Ease of Use:</strong></p><ul><li><p>With a simple API and intuitive hooks, React Hook Form makes it easy to manage form state and validation without the need for complex logic.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Built-in Validation:</strong></p><ul><li><p>The library provides built-in support for synchronous and asynchronous validation, making it easy to enforce rules and display error messages.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Integration with UI Libraries:</strong></p><ul><li><p>React Hook Form works seamlessly with popular UI libraries like Material-UI, Ant Design, and Bootstrap, allowing for easy integration and customization.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Tiny Bundle Size:</strong></p><ul><li><p>The library has a small footprint, ensuring that your application remains lightweight and performant.</p></li></ul></li></ol><p></p><h3>Getting Started with React Hook Form</h3><p>To get started with React Hook Form, you need to have a React application set up. If you don't have one already, you can create a new React application using Create React App:</p><pre><code>npx create-react-app my-app
cd my-app</code></pre><h4>1. Installing React Hook Form</h4><p></p><p>First, install React Hook Form using npm or yarn:</p><pre><code>npm install react-hook-form
# or
yarn add react-hook-form</code></pre><h4>2. Basic Usage</h4><p></p><p>Let's create a simple form to understand the basics of React Hook Form. In this example, we'll create a form with fields for name and email.</p><pre><code>import React from 'react';
import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';

const SimpleForm = () =&gt; {
  const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm();

return (
    &lt;form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;label&gt;Name&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;input {...register('name', { required: true })} /&gt;
        {errors.name &amp;&amp; &lt;span&gt;This field is required&lt;/span&gt;}
      &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;label&gt;Email&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;input {...register('email', { required: true, pattern: /^[^@ ]+@[^@ ]+.[^@ .]{2,}$/ })} /&gt;
        {errors.email &amp;&amp; &lt;span&gt;This field is required and should be a valid email&lt;/span&gt;}
      &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
  );
};

export default SimpleForm;</code></pre><p>In this example:</p><ul><li><p>useForm is used to create a form instance.</p></li><li><p>register is a function that registers the input fields.</p></li><li><p>handleSubmit handles form submission and validation.</p></li><li><p>formState provides form state information, including validation errors.</p></li></ul><h4>3. Advanced Validation</h4><p></p><p>React Hook Form supports advanced validation using custom rules and asynchronous validation. Here's an example with custom validation rules:</p><pre><code>import React from 'react';
import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';

const AdvancedForm = () =&gt; {
  const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm();

return (
    &lt;form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;label&gt;Username&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;input
          {...register('username', {
            required: 'Username is required',
            minLength: {
              value: 3,
              message: 'Username must be at least 3 characters long'
            }
          })}
        /&gt;
        {errors.username &amp;&amp; &lt;span&gt;{errors.username.message}&lt;/span&gt;}
      &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;
        &lt;label&gt;Password&lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;input
          type="password"
          {...register('password', {
            required: 'Password is required',
            validate: (value) =&gt;
              value.length &gt;= 6 || 'Password must be at least 6 characters long'
          })}
        /&gt;
        {errors.password &amp;&amp; &lt;span&gt;{errors.password.message}&lt;/span&gt;}
      &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
  );
};

export default AdvancedForm;</code></pre><p>In this example:</p><ul><li><p>Custom validation rules are added using the <code>register</code> function.</p></li><li><p>Error messages are displayed based on the validation rules.</p></li></ul><h3>Conclusion</h3><p>React Hook Form is a powerful library for managing forms in React applications. Its simplicity, performance optimization, and flexibility make it an excellent choice for handling form state and validation. Whether you're building a simple form or a complex application, React Hook Form provides the tools you need to create efficient and maintainable forms with ease. By following the examples and best practices outlined in this article, you can integrate React Hook Form into your projects and enhance your form handling capabilities.</p><p> </p>`,
    },
  ],
};

const book10 = {
  title: "Get To Know Swagger",
  handle: "swagger",
  state: "Published",

  chapters: [
    {
      title: "What is API Swagger?",
      content: `<p>API Swagger, commonly known as Swagger, is a powerful set of tools and an open-source framework for designing, building, documenting, and consuming RESTful web services. It enables developers to create interactive, machine-readable API documentation that helps improve collaboration, reduces the time needed for API integration, and ensures consistency and accuracy in API development. Swagger simplifies the process of developing APIs by providing clear specifications and interactive documentation.</p><p></p><h3>Key Components of Swagger</h3><p>Swagger consists of several key components that work together to create a seamless experience for API development and documentation:</p><ol><li><p><strong>Swagger Specification (OpenAPI Specification):</strong></p><ul><li><p>The Swagger Specification, now known as the OpenAPI Specification (OAS), is a standard, language-agnostic interface to RESTful APIs. It defines the structure of an API, including endpoints, request and response formats, authentication methods, and more. The specification can be written in YAML or JSON format.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Swagger UI:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Swagger UI is a tool that automatically generates interactive API documentation from an OpenAPI Specification. It provides a web interface that allows users to visualize and interact with the API endpoints, making it easier to understand and test the API.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Swagger Editor:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Swagger Editor is a browser-based editor that allows developers to create and edit OpenAPI Specifications in a user-friendly interface. It provides real-time validation, auto-completion, and syntax highlighting, making it easier to write and maintain API specifications.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Swagger Codegen:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Swagger Codegen is a tool that generates client libraries, server stubs, API documentation, and configuration automatically from an OpenAPI Specification. It supports various programming languages and frameworks, enabling developers to quickly integrate with APIs.</p></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>SwaggerHub:</strong></p><ul><li><p>SwaggerHub is a collaborative platform for API development that combines the capabilities of Swagger tools with additional features for team collaboration, versioning, and hosting of OpenAPI Specifications. It streamlines the API development lifecycle and ensures consistency across teams.</p></li></ul></li></ol><h3>Example of a Swagger Specification</h3><pre><code>openapi: 3.0.0
info:
  title: Simple API
  version: 1.0.0
paths:
  /users:
    get:
      summary: Retrieve a list of users
      responses:
        '200':
          description: A list of users
          content:
            application/json:
              schema:
                type: array
                items:
                  type: object
                  properties:
                    id:
                      type: integer
                      example: 1
                    name:
                      type: string
                      example: John Doe
  /users/{id}:
    get:
      summary: Retrieve a user by ID
      parameters:
        - name: id
          in: path
          required: true
          schema:
            type: integer
      responses:
        '200':
          description: A user object
          content:
            application/json:
              schema:
                type: object
                properties:
                  id:
                    type: integer
                    example: 1
                  name:
                    type: string
                    example: John Doe
        '404':
          description: User not found</code></pre><h3>Conclusion</h3><p>Swagger is an invaluable tool for API development, providing clear, interactive, and machine-readable documentation that improves collaboration and streamlines the API lifecycle. By adopting Swagger and the OpenAPI Specification, developers can create more consistent, maintainable, and user-friendly APIs, ultimately enhancing the overall development experience.</p>`,
    },
  ],
};

